47 | **+\u20b915,262** |\n| Return | \u22121.99% | +6.11% |\n| Max drawdown | \u2212\u20b940,063 (\u221216.2%) | \u2212\u20b925,461 (\u22129.9%) |\n\n**Read (genuinely surprising direction, but it makes sense):**\n- **No stop wins on every metric here** \u2014 higher P&L, higher win rate, *and* smaller drawdown in rupees. The 25% stop was actively hurting you.\n- **Why:** on an intraday short straddle, premium routinely spikes intraday and then decays back by 15:15. A 25% stop converts those temporary spikes into realized losses, and because you square off *one* leg on stop, you often crystallize the loss right before time-decay would have bailed you out. Removing the stop lets the theta play out \u2014 hence 71% win rate.\n- **Important caveat \u2014 the drawdown looks better but the risk profile is not truly \"safer.\"** A naked short straddle with no stop has *unlimited* tail risk. Over these 56 quiet-ish days the max loss stayed at \u2212\u20b925k, but a single gap or trend day could produce a loss far larger than anything the stopped version would allow. The stop caps catastrophe; it just cost money in this sample.\n\n**Bottom line:** in this backtest, no-stop is clearly better on P&L and even drawdown \u2014 but that's partly because the sample had no disaster day. If you're trading this live, the real question isn't \"stop vs no stop,\" it's **how** to cap tail risk without getting whipsawed.\n\nBetter next step: test a **move-SL-to-cost** or a **whole-strategy MTM stop** (e.g. \u2212\u20b98k), which protects the tail without the intraday-spike whipsaw of a tight per-leg stop. Want me to run that?", "results": [], "cost": {"usd": 0.037073, "in_tokens": 8003, "out_tokens": 751, "llm_calls": 1, "backtests": 0}}, {"role": "user", "content": "Which of everything I've tested so far had the best risk-adjusted return?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "Good question \u2014 let me compare on a risk-adjusted basis (return per unit of drawdown), not just raw P&L. Note upfront: your runs span **different instruments, time windows, and capital bases**, so this is a rough ranking, not apples-to-apples.\n\n**Equity strategies** (all \u20b910L capital, but different periods):\n| Strategy | Period | Return | Max DD (\u20b9) | Return/DD |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Donchian breakout + RSI | 2022\u201326 (4.5y) | +76.2% (13.5% CAGR) | \u2212\u20b9236k | ~0.32 |\n| 60-day Momentum + 8% trail | 2022\u201326 (4.5y) | +71.7% (12.85% CAGR) | \u2212\u20b9263k | ~0.27 |\n| Bollinger Mean Reversion | 2021\u201326 (5.5y) | +34.4% (5.55% CAGR) | \u2212\u20b9258k | ~0.13 |\n\n**Options strategies** (short straddle, ~\u20b92.5L margin):\n| Strategy | Period | Return | Max DD (\u20b9) | Return/DD |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| No-SL straddle | full 56d | +6.11% | \u2212\u20b925.5k | ~0.60 |\n| June, \u20b93k target | 21d | ~+4.1% | \u2212\u20b912.5k | ~0.86 |\n| June, 25% SL | 21d | +1.92% | \u2212\u20b98.9k | ~0.56 |\n| 25% SL | full 56d | \u22121.99% | \u2212\u20b940k | negative |\n\n**Honest answer \u2014 it depends on what \"best\" means:**\n\n- **On raw return/drawdown ratio**, the short options plays look best (0.6\u20130.86). But that's misleading: they cover only **21\u201356 days**, so the drawdown simply hasn't had time to show its worst. A naked straddle's real risk is a tail day that isn't in this tiny sample. I would **not** trust those ratios.\n\n- **On a trustworthy, risk-adjusted basis**, the **Donchian breakout + RSI filter** is the strongest: +13.5% CAGR over **4.5 years** with a \u221223.6% drawdown (return/DD \u2248 0.32). It earned that ratio across many market regimes and hundreds of trades (752) \u2014 a far more reliable read than 21\u201356 options days.\n\n**Bottom line:** Donchian breakout is your best *credible* risk-adjusted result. The options ratios look higher only because their short windows understate tail risk \u2014 don't rank them ahead on that basis.\n\nOne caveat: even the equity Sharpe-style comparison is imperfect because periods differ (Bollinger includes 2021). If you want a clean equity ranking, I can re-run all three over the **identical window** (say 2022\u20132026). Want that?", "results": [], "cost": {"usd": 0.045378, "in_tokens": 8779, "out_tokens": 928, "llm_calls": 1, "backtests": 0}}]}